# Camera state

```js
const camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
const cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
```

And a particle array:

```js
let particles = [];
let tick = 0;
```

---

# Main helper

## Find node by id

```js
function getNode(id) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}
```

---

# Core simulation step

## 1. Pairwise attraction between all nodes

This section computes force between every pair:

```js
force = config.attraction / (distance * distance)
```

and applies it along the direction between them.

So every node attracts every other node, like a simplified gravity.

---

## 2. Spring forces on linked pairs

For each spring:

```js
stretch = distance - rest
force = k * stretch
```

Then it pushes/pulls the two nodes to maintain the target distance.

That’s standard Hooke’s law spring behavior.

---

## 3. Damping and centering

For each node:

```js
node.vx += (400 - node.x) * config.centering;
node.vy += (300 - node.y) * config.centering;

node.vx *= config.amplification; // really damping
node.vy *= config.amplification;

node.x += node.vx;
node.y += node.vy;
```

So:

- `(400, 300)` is the center of the scene
- nodes are gently pulled toward center
- velocity decays by multiplying by `0.92`

---

# Particle spawning

This function creates little drifting particles from random nodes.

Deobfuscated:

```js
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= config.streamLimit) return;

  const source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  const angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  const speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT1_2;

  particles.push({
    x: source.x,
    y: source.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT1_2
  });
}
```

So particles:

- start at a random node
- move in a random direction
- have finite lifetime
- have random size

---

# Particle update

```js
function updateParticles() {
  for (let i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    const p = particles[i];
    p.age++;
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;

    p.vx *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;
    p.vy *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;

    if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
      particles.splice(i, 1);
    }
  }
}
```

So particles slowly slow down and disappear when old.

---

# Camera smoothing

```js
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * config.theta;
  camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.theta;
}
```

This is simple interpolation / easing.

---

# Main loop

```js
function tickFrame() {
  updateNodes();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();

  if (tick % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
  tick++;
}

setInterval(tickFrame, 10);
```

So:

- physics updates every 10 ms
- a particle is spawned every 3 ticks
- that’s about every 30 ms, capped at 40 particles

